<!-- ═══ PAGE 2: AI 101 ════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page" id="page-2">
  <div class="page-header" style="--accent-glow:rgba(59,130,246,.15)">
    <div class="page-eyebrow"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--ai101)"></div>Section 02 · Foundation</div>
    <h1>📖 AI 101 — Start Here</h1>
    <p class="lead">Before we use the tools, we need to understand what they actually are. This section breaks down the big ideas behind AI in plain language — no computer science degree needed.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="page-body">

    <div class="callout">Knowing what's under the hood doesn't make you a mechanic — it makes you a better driver. You'll understand why AI is brilliant at some things, terrible at others, and how to work with both.</div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(96,165,250,.12)">🤔</div>
        <div><h2>What Even Is AI?</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p><strong>Artificial Intelligence</strong> is software that can do things that normally require human thinking — like understanding language, recognizing images, writing stories, solving problems, or having a conversation.</p>
        <p>But here's the key thing most people misunderstand: <strong>AI doesn't actually think. It doesn't have ideas or opinions or feelings.</strong> What it does is find and reproduce patterns from an enormous amount of data it was trained on.</p>
        <p>Here's a simpler way to think about it: instead of programming a computer with a list of rules ("a dog has 4 legs, fur, and barks"), you show it ten million pictures of dogs and let it figure out the pattern itself. After enough examples, it just <em>knows</em> what a dog looks like — without anyone ever telling it the rules. That's the core idea behind modern AI.</p>
        <p>The type of AI we use today — ChatGPT, Claude, Gemini — is called a <strong>Large Language Model</strong>. Instead of learning from images, it learned from text. Billions of web pages, books, articles, and conversations, processed until it understood the patterns of language well enough to generate its own.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(252,211,77,.12)">⏳</div>
        <div><h2>A Quick History</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"><p>AI didn't appear overnight. It's been building for 70 years — but the last decade changed everything.</p></div>
      <div class="timeline">
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">1950s</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>The Idea Is Born</h4><p>Alan Turing asks "Can machines think?" and proposes the Turing Test. The concept of AI is formally introduced. It's entirely theoretical — the hardware doesn't exist yet to do anything serious.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">1960s–70s</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>Early Optimism, Early Limits</h4><p>Researchers build early programs that can play chess and solve simple logic problems. Everyone thinks "we'll have human-level AI in 20 years." They were wrong. It was much harder than expected.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">1980s–90s</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>Rule-Based Systems</h4><p>AI shifts to "expert systems" — huge if/then rule trees coded by hand. They worked for narrow tasks but were brittle and expensive to maintain. IBM's Deep Blue beats chess champion Garry Kasparov in 1997.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">2012</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>The Deep Learning Breakthrough</h4><p>A neural network called AlexNet crushes the competition at an image recognition contest. Deep learning — using layers of artificial neurons — proves it can learn patterns from data better than any hand-coded system. The modern AI era begins.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">2017</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>Google Invents the Transformer</h4><p>Google researchers publish a paper called "Attention Is All You Need." The Transformer architecture is the engine that powers every major AI model today — GPT, Claude, Gemini, all of them. This is the single most important technical breakthrough in modern AI.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">2020</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>GPT-3 — AI Writes Like a Human</h4><p>OpenAI releases GPT-3 with 175 billion parameters. For the first time, an AI can write essays, code, poetry, and hold conversations that are genuinely hard to distinguish from human writing. Developers start building products on top of it immediately.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">2022</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>ChatGPT Goes Mainstream</h4><p>OpenAI releases ChatGPT on November 30th. One hundred million people sign up in two months — the fastest product adoption in history. AI stops being a developer tool and becomes something everyone uses. The world permanently changes.</p></div></div>
        <div class="timeline-item"><div class="timeline-year">2024–25</div><div class="timeline-content"><h4>The Agent Era Begins</h4><p>AI stops just answering questions and starts taking actions. Agents that can browse the web, write and run code, manage files, and complete multi-step tasks autonomously become real and accessible. The shift from AI as a chatbot to AI as a collaborator is underway.</p></div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(52,211,153,.12)">📚</div>
        <div><h2>Key Terms Everyone Should Know</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"><p>These are the terms you'll see everywhere. Know them cold.</p></div>
      <div class="glossary">
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Machine Learning (ML)</div><div class="def">Teaching a computer by showing it examples instead of writing explicit rules. The computer finds the patterns in the data itself.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Neural Network</div><div class="def">A system loosely inspired by the brain — layers of connected nodes that each recognize a small piece of a pattern. Stack enough layers, and you get something very powerful.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">LLM</div><div class="def">Large Language Model. An AI trained on massive amounts of text. What ChatGPT, Claude, and Gemini all are at their core.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Training</div><div class="def">The process where an AI studies enormous amounts of data, adjusting its internal settings billions of times until it gets good at a task.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Parameters</div><div class="def">The billions of numerical settings inside an AI model that get adjusted during training. Think of them as the model's memory and knowledge — more parameters generally means more capable.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Foundation Model</div><div class="def">A massive AI model trained on general knowledge that can be adapted for many different tasks. GPT-4, Claude, and Gemini are all foundation models.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Inference</div><div class="def">When a trained model actually generates a response. Training is when it learns; inference is when it works.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Fine-Tuning</div><div class="def">Taking a pre-trained foundation model and doing additional training on a specific dataset to make it better at a particular task or style.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Open Source</div><div class="def">An AI model whose code and weights are publicly available. Anyone can run it, modify it, or build on it. Meta's Llama models are a major example.</div></div>
        <div class="term-card"><div class="term">Multimodal</div><div class="def">An AI that can work with multiple types of input — text, images, audio, video. Most modern flagship models are multimodal.</div></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(167,139,250,.12)">🏢</div>
        <div><h2>The Big Players Right Now</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"><p>You'll keep hearing these names. Know who they are and what they're building.</p></div>
      <table class="compare-table">
        <tr><th>Company</th><th>Model</th><th>Known For</th></tr>
        <tr><td>OpenAI</td><td>GPT-4o, o1, o3</td><td>The pioneer. Created ChatGPT and the modern AI wave. Backed by Microsoft. Most widely used consumer AI.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Anthropic</td><td>Claude 3.5, Claude Sonnet</td><td>Founded by ex-OpenAI researchers focused on safety. Claude is known for long-form reasoning, nuance, and following complex instructions.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Google DeepMind</td><td>Gemini 1.5 Pro / Flash</td><td>Google's combined AI lab. Massive context windows, connected to Google Search, strong at multimodal tasks.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Meta AI</td><td>Llama 3</td><td>Open-source giant. Llama models are free to download and run locally. Huge developer ecosystem built on top of them.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Mistral</td><td>Mistral 7B, Mixtral</td><td>European AI lab making highly efficient models — smaller size, strong performance. Popular for local and enterprise use.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>xAI (Elon Musk)</td><td>Grok</td><td>Integrated into X (Twitter). Has access to real-time X data. Known for a less restricted style.</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="challenges-wrap">
      <h2>🏋️ Hands-On Challenges</h2>
      <p class="cw-sub">Moving AI 101 from something you read about to something you actually know.</p>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 1 — History From Memory</h4>
        <p>Close this page. On a blank piece of paper, write down as many key moments in AI history as you can remember — in order. Don't look. When done, check back and see what you missed. The gaps are exactly what to revisit.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 2 — The Key Terms Quiz</h4>
        <p>Without looking at the glossary, explain in your own words: What is an LLM? What is training? What does "open source" mean for AI? If you can say it simply, you understand it. If you're reaching for the right words, go back and read the glossary once more — then try again.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 3 — Live Model Check</h4>
        <p>Search right now: "latest AI models 2025." Find the current flagship models from OpenAI, Anthropic, and Google. Write their names down. This landscape shifts fast — the habit of checking in on it periodically is worth building early.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 4 — Have a Real Conversation</h4>
        <p>Open Claude, ChatGPT, and Gemini. Ask all three: <em>"Explain what you are in simple terms, like I'm hearing about AI for the first time."</em> Compare. Which answer is clearest? Which is most accurate? What's different about each one's personality?</p>
