<!-- ═══ PAGE 3: PROMPTING ════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page" id="page-3">
  <div class="page-header" style="--accent-glow:rgba(245,158,11,.12)">
    <div class="page-eyebrow"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--prompt)"></div>Section 03 · Core Skill</div>
    <h1>💬 Prompting — The Core Skill</h1>
    <p class="lead">Prompting is the most important skill to learn in the AI era. It's how you communicate with AI — and the difference between a mediocre output and a great one almost always comes down to the quality of the prompt.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="page-body">

    <div class="callout">A bad prompt gives a bad answer. A great prompt gives a great answer. The good news: this is an entirely learnable skill, and you can get noticeably better in a single afternoon of practice.</div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(252,211,77,.12)">📝</div>
        <div><h2>What Is a Prompt, Really?</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>A <strong>prompt</strong> is the message you send to an AI. But it's more than just a question — it's an instruction, a context, a request, and a set of constraints all bundled into one. The AI can only work with what you give it.</p>
        <p>Think of it like briefing a contractor. A contractor who shows up with just "build me a house" will either ask a hundred follow-up questions or start building something completely wrong. A contractor who gets a detailed brief — style, budget, timeline, must-haves, deal-breakers — can actually build what you want.</p>
        <p><strong>AI is the same. The quality of your output is almost always a direct reflection of the quality of your input.</strong> If the output isn't great, the first thing to fix is the prompt, not the AI.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <hr class="divider">

    <div class="level-block">
      <div class="level-header">
        <div class="level-badge" style="background:rgba(96,165,250,.15);color:#60A5FA">Level 1</div>
        <div><h3>The Basics</h3><p class="sub">These four rules alone will make your prompts 10x better</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-body">
        <ul class="content-list">
          <li><strong>Be specific.</strong> "Write a short email" is vague. "Write a 3-sentence email to a client explaining we'll be 2 days late on a project. Keep it professional, apologetic but not over-the-top, and offer a new deadline." That's specific. The more detail you give, the closer the output is to what you actually wanted.</li>
          <li><strong>Give context.</strong> Tell the AI who you are, what you're trying to accomplish, and why. It doesn't know anything about your situation unless you tell it. "I'm a freelance designer pitching a new client" changes every response it gives you.</li>
          <li><strong>Specify the format.</strong> Do you want a bulleted list or a paragraph? Short or long? An email or a social post? A numbered step-by-step or a casual explanation? Say it out loud. If you don't say, the AI guesses — and it might guess wrong.</li>
          <li><strong>Specify the tone.</strong> Professional, conversational, blunt, encouraging, simple like I'm explaining to a 12-year-old, funny, serious. Tone shapes everything. "Write this for a boardroom vs. write this for a text message" produces completely different results.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="level-block">
      <div class="level-header">
        <div class="level-badge" style="background:rgba(52,211,153,.15);color:#34D399">Level 2</div>
        <div><h3>Intermediate Techniques</h3><p class="sub">Once the basics feel natural, layer these in</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-body">
        <ul class="content-list">
          <li><strong>Few-shot prompting.</strong> Show the AI exactly what you want by giving it 1–3 examples first. "Here are three examples of the kind of caption I write: [example 1], [example 2], [example 3]. Now write one for this photo: [description]." The AI matches the style precisely instead of guessing.</li>
          <li><strong>Chain of thought.</strong> For complex questions, add "think through this step by step before answering." This tells the AI to slow down and reason carefully instead of jumping to a first answer. Try it on a hard problem and compare the output to asking normally — the difference is noticeable.</li>
          <li><strong>Role prompting.</strong> Assign the AI a specific identity. "You are a senior UX designer with 15 years of experience. Review this user flow and tell me what's wrong." The role shifts how it frames its answer, how much depth it goes into, and what assumptions it makes. Very powerful for getting expert-level responses.</li>
          <li><strong>Iterate, don't restart.</strong> Your first prompt doesn't need to be perfect. Get an output, then say "make it shorter," "change the tone to casual," "now add a specific example of X," "rewrite the opening." This is a conversation, not a one-shot command. The best outputs usually come after 3–5 rounds of iteration.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask for options.</strong> Instead of "write me a headline," say "give me 5 different headline options — one bold, one minimal, one question-based, one data-driven, one conversational." Then pick the best one or combine elements.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="level-block">
      <div class="level-header">
        <div class="level-badge" style="background:rgba(167,139,250,.15);color:#C084FC">Level 3</div>
        <div><h3>Advanced Moves</h3><p class="sub">These unlock a completely different tier of output quality</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="level-body">
        <ul class="content-list">
          <li><strong>System prompts.</strong> A system prompt is a hidden instruction at the start of a conversation that shapes how the AI behaves for the entire session. Many tools let you set this. Example: "You are a concise assistant. Always respond in plain language, under 200 words, using active voice. Never use jargon." Now every response in that session follows those rules automatically.</li>
          <li><strong>Constraints as creative tools.</strong> "Do this in under 100 words." "Don't use bullet points." "Only reference information I provide — don't use outside knowledge." "Write this without using the words 'powerful,' 'innovative,' or 'seamless.'" Constraints force precision. They're counterintuitively one of the best ways to get better outputs.</li>
          <li><strong>Ask it to critique itself.</strong> After getting a response, ask: "What are the weaknesses in this answer?" or "What important things did you leave out?" or "If you were a harsh critic of this response, what would you say?" The AI will surface things it glossed over or got wrong. Then you can ask it to fix those specific things.</li>
          <li><strong>Prompt chaining.</strong> Break a big, complex task into sequential steps. Complete step 1, use that output as the input for step 2, and so on. Example: Step 1 — "Outline the main argument for this essay." Step 2 — "Expand section 2 of that outline into a full paragraph." Step 3 — "Now write a strong closing paragraph that ties back to the opening." Each step builds on the last.</li>
          <li><strong>Meta-prompting.</strong> Ask the AI to help you write a better prompt. "I want to get great results from AI for [task]. Help me write the best possible prompt to get that result." Then use the prompt it gives you. The AI knows what it responds to.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(248,113,113,.12)">❌</div>
        <div><h2>Common Mistakes to Stop Making</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"></div>
      <div class="cards-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🌫️</div><h3>Being Too Vague</h3><p>"Help me with my business" tells the AI almost nothing. It'll give you something generic. The more specific, the better the output.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🛑</div><h3>Accepting the First Output</h3><p>The second or third response is almost always better than the first. Iterate. Push back. Ask it to try again differently.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔍</div><h3>Treating It Like Google</h3><p>AI works better with full sentences, context, and goals — not short search-style keywords. Write to it like you'd brief a smart person.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">👤</div><h3>Forgetting the Audience</h3><p>Who is this output for? A 10-year-old, a CEO, a tech team, a first-time customer? Not specifying the audience means the AI will guess, and it might guess wrong.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">📏</div><h3>Skipping Length and Format</h3><p>Do you want 3 sentences or 3 paragraphs? A table or a list? Casual or formal? These small specifications prevent most of the "this isn't quite right" moments.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔒</div><h3>Not Using Context</h3><p>If you're working on an ongoing project, paste in the relevant background at the start of every session. AI doesn't remember previous conversations unless you tell it.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="challenges-wrap">
      <h2>🏋️ Hands-On Challenges</h2>
      <p class="cw-sub">Prompting is a physical skill. It only develops through reps.</p>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 1 — The Same Task, 5 Ways</h4>
        <p>Pick one task — write a bio, explain a concept, create a plan. Write 5 completely different prompts for that exact task. Compare the 5 outputs side by side. Write one observation: what made the best prompt the best?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 2 — Rescue a Bad Prompt</h4>
        <p>Think of a time AI gave you a frustrating or useless answer. Recreate that original prompt. Then rewrite it using what you now know — add context, a role, a format, a tone, a constraint. Compare the new output to the old one.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 3 — Chain of Thought in Action</h4>
        <p>Ask AI a genuinely complex question. First, ask it normally. Then ask the same question again but add "think through this step by step before answering." Compare the two responses. Which one catches more nuance?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 4 — Critique the AI</h4>
        <p>Get any response from the AI. Then say "Now tell me: what are the 3 biggest weaknesses or gaps in what you just wrote?" See what it surfaces. Then ask it to fix those things. This is one of the most powerful prompting habits you can build.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 5 — Iterate 5 Rounds</h4>
        <p>Start with a vague, low-quality prompt. Get the output. Then give one specific piece of feedback. Repeat 5 times in a row on the same task. Notice how dramatically the output changes by round 4 and 5. That's the power of iteration.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
