<!-- ═══ PAGE 4: LLMs ══════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page" id="page-4">
  <div class="page-header" style="--accent-glow:rgba(6,182,212,.12)">
    <div class="page-eyebrow"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--llm)"></div>Section 04 · Under the Hood</div>
    <h1>🔧 How LLMs Actually Work</h1>
    <p class="lead">You don't need to be an engineer. But knowing the basics of how these models work will make you a fundamentally better user — you'll understand why they're brilliant at some things and why they fail at others.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="page-body">

    <div class="callout">Think of this as understanding how a car works at a basic level. You don't need to be a mechanic. But knowing that the engine needs fuel, that brakes have limits, and that checking tire pressure matters — that knowledge makes you a safer, smarter driver.</div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(34,211,238,.12)">🎯</div>
        <div><h2>What an LLM Actually Does</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>An <strong>LLM (Large Language Model)</strong> is trained by processing an enormous amount of text — billions of web pages, books, articles, code, and conversations. During training, it adjusts its internal settings billions of times to get better at one specific task: <strong>predicting the next word in a sequence.</strong></p>
        <p>When you send a message, the model reads your entire message and predicts the most appropriate next word. Then it predicts the word after that. Then the word after that. It does this thousands of times in a fraction of a second until it has produced a full response.</p>
        <p>That's the whole trick. <strong>An LLM is an extraordinarily good next-word predictor.</strong> The reason it seems to "understand" things is because predicting the right next word at that level of complexity requires capturing the structure, meaning, logic, and nuance of language in a way that looks a lot like comprehension.</p>
        <p>It's not magic. It's not consciousness. It's pattern recognition at a scale that produces something that looks surprisingly intelligent.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(252,211,77,.12)">🧵</div>
        <div><h2>Tokens — How AI Reads Text</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>AI doesn't read words the way we do. It breaks text into small chunks called <strong>tokens</strong>. A token is roughly 3–4 characters, or about ¾ of a word on average. "Artificial intelligence is fascinating" might be split into tokens like: "Art", "ificial", " intelligence", " is", " fas", "cin", "ating."</p>
        <p>Why does this matter? Two reasons:</p>
        <p><strong>1. Token limits.</strong> Models have a maximum number of tokens they can process at once — both in what you send them and what they send back. Knowing this helps you understand why very long conversations or documents sometimes need to be broken up.</p>
        <p><strong>2. Token cost.</strong> When using AI through APIs, you're usually billed by the token. Longer, more verbose prompts cost more. Understanding tokens helps you be more efficient — especially when scaling up to automated workflows.</p>
        <p>The practical takeaway: tokens are small. Most modern models can handle tens of thousands of tokens in a single conversation — enough for a very long session — but not unlimited.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(96,165,250,.12)">🧠</div>
        <div><h2>The Context Window — AI's Working Memory</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>Every LLM has a <strong>context window</strong> — the maximum amount of text it can "see" and reason about at one time. Think of it as the AI's working memory.</p>
        <p>Everything in your current conversation lives in the context window: your messages, the AI's responses, any files you've shared, and any background instructions. The AI can reference anything in that window when generating a response.</p>
        <p>But here's the critical limitation: <strong>once the conversation exceeds the context window, the oldest content gets pushed out and the AI loses access to it.</strong> It doesn't "forget" in the way humans do — it literally can no longer see that text anymore.</p>
        <p>This is why long conversations can lead to inconsistency or the AI forgetting something you said early on. The fix is simple: for long projects, summarize key points periodically, or start new conversations and paste in the relevant context at the beginning.</p>
        <p>Context window sizes are growing fast. Older models: 4,000–8,000 tokens. Modern models: 128,000–2,000,000+ tokens. The longer the context, the more complex and continuous the work you can do.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(52,211,153,.12)">🌡️</div>
        <div><h2>Temperature — The Creativity Dial</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p><strong>Temperature</strong> is a setting that controls how predictable vs. creative the AI's output is. It ranges from 0 (completely deterministic, always the same output) to 1 or higher (much more random and creative).</p>
        <p>At <strong>low temperature</strong>: the AI picks the most likely, most expected next word every time. Outputs are consistent, factual, and reliable. Great for summarizing, extracting information, writing code, answering factual questions.</p>
        <p>At <strong>high temperature</strong>: the AI takes more creative risks — picking less obvious words and surprising connections. Outputs are more varied and interesting but also more likely to drift or hallucinate. Great for creative writing, brainstorming, ideation.</p>
        <p>Most AI apps don't expose temperature directly — they set it for you based on context. But knowing it exists helps you understand why the same prompt sometimes gives slightly different answers, and why asking the AI to "be more creative" on a rewrite actually does something under the hood.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(248,113,113,.12)">👻</div>
        <div><h2>Hallucinations — Why AI Makes Things Up</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>This is one of the most important things to understand about LLMs: <strong>they sometimes state false information with complete confidence.</strong> This is called a <em>hallucination</em>, and it's not a bug that's been fixed — it's a fundamental property of how these models work.</p>
        <p>Remember, the model is always predicting the most likely next word. Sometimes the most likely-sounding continuation of a sentence is factually wrong. The model doesn't have a separate "fact checker" it consults — it just produces what statistically fits the pattern of language it learned.</p>
        <p>This shows up most commonly with: specific dates, statistics, names of real people, recent events (after the training cutoff), citations and sources, and highly specific or obscure facts.</p>
        <p><strong>The practical rule: never trust AI on specific facts without verifying them independently.</strong> For general reasoning, creative tasks, drafting, summarizing your own content, brainstorming — hallucinations rarely matter. For factual claims you'll share with others, always double-check.</p>
        <p>Good models have gotten better at saying "I'm not sure" or "you should verify this." But they still hallucinate. Being aware of this makes you a far more careful and effective AI user than most people.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(167,139,250,.12)">🔁</div>
        <div><h2>Training Cutoffs &amp; Model Versions</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>Every LLM has a <strong>training cutoff</strong> — a date after which it has no knowledge of world events. If something happened after that date, the model doesn't know about it. This is why asking AI about very recent news can lead to wrong answers or "I don't have information about that."</p>
        <p>Models deal with this in two ways: some are connected to web search tools that let them look things up in real time. Others are purely based on their training data and will be upfront about their cutoff date.</p>
        <p>Model versions are worth understanding too. When you see "GPT-4o" or "Claude 3.5 Sonnet" — those are specific versions. Newer versions are generally: smarter, faster, better at following complex instructions, have larger context windows, and are more safety-aware. But bigger isn't always better — sometimes a smaller, faster model is exactly what you need for a simple task.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="challenges-wrap">
      <h2>🏋️ Hands-On Challenges</h2>
      <p class="cw-sub">Make these concepts real by actually experiencing them, not just reading about them.</p>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 1 — Catch a Hallucination</h4>
        <p>Ask an AI about something very specific and obscure — a minor historical figure, a niche statistic, a local event. Then fact-check the answer on Google or Wikipedia. Did it make anything up? How confident did it sound? Write down exactly what it got wrong and how it was phrased.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 2 — Break the Context Window</h4>
        <p>At the very start of a conversation with Claude or ChatGPT, mention something specific and unusual — a made-up word, a specific number, a fake name you invented. Chat about completely different topics for a while. Then ask: "What was the specific thing I mentioned at the very beginning of our conversation?" Did it remember?</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 3 — Explain It Back</h4>
        <p>Without notes: explain to the other person what tokens are, what the context window is, and what hallucinations are — using completely different analogies than the ones in this section. Your own analogies. If you can create a new analogy that makes the concept clear, you genuinely understand it.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 4 — Temperature Experiment</h4>
        <p>Ask Claude: "Write a one-paragraph opening for a story about a city that never sleeps." Then ask: "Write it again, but make it unexpected, strange, and surprising — take creative risks." Compare. That second instruction is effectively asking for higher temperature. Notice how the language choices change.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

