<!-- ═══ PAGE 5: AGENTS ═══════════════════════════════════════ -->
<div class="page" id="page-5">
  <div class="page-header" style="--accent-glow:rgba(236,72,153,.12)">
    <div class="page-eyebrow"><div class="dot" style="background:var(--agents)"></div>Section 05 · The Frontier</div>
    <h1>🤖 AI Agents — The Next Level</h1>
    <p class="lead">If LLMs are the engine, agents are the whole car — with GPS, hands, and a plan. This is the most exciting, fastest-moving part of AI right now. Most people barely understand it yet. We're going deep.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="page-body">

    <div class="callout">This section is longer than the others because it deserves to be. Agents represent a fundamental shift in what AI can do — from answering questions to getting things done. Understanding this is what separates AI users from AI <em>builders</em>.</div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(244,114,182,.12)">🤔</div>
        <div><h2>What Is an Agent, Really?</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>A regular AI like ChatGPT is <strong>reactive</strong> — it waits for you, reads your message, generates a response, and stops. One turn. That's it. You're always in the driver's seat.</p>
        <p>An <strong>AI agent</strong> is different. It's <em>autonomous</em>. You give it a goal, and it figures out the steps, takes actions, checks its work, adjusts when something goes wrong, and keeps going until the task is complete — with minimal input from you.</p>
        <p>The difference is the difference between a calculator and an assistant. A calculator waits for you to push buttons. An assistant hears "plan my trip to Chicago" and goes and does it — books the flight, finds the hotel, checks the weather, puts it all in a calendar invite, and sends you a summary.</p>
        <p><strong>Agents can perceive information, reason about what to do, take real actions in the world, and learn from what happens.</strong> That's a completely different category of tool.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(252,211,77,.12)">🏗️</div>
        <div><h2>The Four Parts of Every Agent</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"><p>No matter how complex or simple, every AI agent is made of the same four things:</p></div>
      <div class="cards-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🧠</div><h3>The Brain (LLM)</h3><p>The model doing all the thinking — Claude, GPT-4, Gemini, etc. It reads every input, reasons about what to do next, and decides which tools to use and when. The brain is what makes an agent intelligent vs. just automated.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">💾</div><h3>Memory</h3><p>How the agent keeps track of everything that has happened. At the basic level: the conversation history. More advanced: external databases that persist information across sessions so the agent can remember things from a week ago.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🛠️</div><h3>Tools</h3><p>The agent's "hands." Tools let it take real actions — search the web, run code, send emails, read files, call APIs, take screenshots, click buttons. Without tools, an agent can think but can't act.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">📋</div><h3>Instructions</h3><p>The hidden rules given to the agent at the start — its role, its personality, what it's allowed to do, what tools it has access to, how to behave when uncertain. This is what makes a general AI model into a specific agent.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(34,211,238,.12)">🗺️</div>
        <div><h2>How Agents Think and Plan</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"><p>Different agents use different strategies to reason through tasks. The main approaches:</p></div>
      <table class="compare-table">
        <tr><th>Strategy</th><th>How It Works</th><th>Best For</th></tr>
        <tr><td>ReAct</td><td>Alternates between reasoning ("I need to find X") and acting (search for it), over and over until done. The most common approach.</td><td>Most everyday agentic tasks. Simple, reliable, widely used.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Plan-and-Execute</td><td>Makes a full step-by-step plan first, then executes each step in order.</td><td>Complex, predictable tasks. Struggles if the situation changes mid-task.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Chain of Thought</td><td>Forced to "think out loud" step by step before doing anything. Shows its work.</td><td>Problems where the reasoning process is as important as the answer.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Tree of Thoughts</td><td>Explores multiple possible approaches simultaneously, like a chess player, then picks the most promising path.</td><td>Hard problems with multiple valid solutions. Expensive but powerful.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Self-Reflection</td><td>Reviews its own outputs and asks "Is this right? What could I have missed?" before finishing.</td><td>High-stakes tasks where accuracy matters more than speed.</td></tr>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(96,165,250,.12)">💾</div>
        <div><h2>How Agents Remember Things</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>Memory is one of the hardest problems in agent design. Here's how different types of memory work:</p>
      </div>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong>Short-term memory (in-context).</strong> The current conversation. Everything the agent has seen in this session. Fast and always available — but limited by the context window and wiped when the session ends.</li>
        <li><strong>Long-term memory (external storage).</strong> A database outside the model. The agent writes important information there and retrieves it later. This is how an agent can remember your preferences, past projects, or important facts from months ago.</li>
        <li><strong>RAG (Retrieval-Augmented Generation).</strong> Instead of trying to memorize everything, the agent searches a library of documents to find relevant information at the moment it needs it. Like open-book vs. closed-book. Makes agents much more accurate on specialized topics.</li>
        <li><strong>Episodic memory.</strong> A record of specific past experiences — "last time I handled a task like this, I tried X and it failed, so I'll try Y instead." Still cutting-edge. Most commercial agents don't have this yet, but it's coming.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(167,139,250,.12)">🛠️</div>
        <div><h2>The Tools Agents Use</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body"></div>
      <div class="cards-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔍</div><h3>Web Search</h3><p>Look up live, current information. Critical for anything time-sensitive or that happened after the training cutoff.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🖥️</div><h3>Browser / Computer Use</h3><p>Actually open websites, click buttons, fill forms, take screenshots. The agent operates a real browser. This is new and powerful.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">💻</div><h3>Code Interpreter</h3><p>Write and actually run code. Do math, analyze data, create files, process spreadsheets. The agent produces and executes programs.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">📁</div><h3>File Tools</h3><p>Read PDFs, Word docs, spreadsheets, images. Write and save new files. Essential for any document-based workflow.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">📧</div><h3>Email &amp; Calendar</h3><p>Send emails, read your inbox, schedule meetings, set reminders. Connects AI to your communication layer.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔗</div><h3>APIs</h3><p>Connect to virtually any platform: Slack, Notion, Airtable, Google Sheets, Stripe, GitHub, and thousands more. The agent becomes a hub between all your tools.</p></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(52,211,153,.12)">👥</div>
        <div><h2>Multi-Agent Systems — Teams of AI</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>One agent is powerful. A coordinated team of agents is transformative.</p>
        <p>The idea: instead of one generalist agent trying to do everything, you build a team of specialized agents — each excellent at its specific job — with an orchestrator managing them and routing work to the right specialist.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="cards-grid">
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">👑</div><h3>Orchestrator</h3><p>The manager. Receives the main goal, breaks it into subtasks, assigns each task to the right specialist agent, collects the outputs, and assembles the final result.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔬</div><h3>Research Agent</h3><p>Specializes in finding and synthesizing information. Uses web search, reads documents, extracts key facts. Feeds its output to other agents.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">✍️</div><h3>Writing Agent</h3><p>Specializes in creating polished text. Takes research and outlines and turns them into well-crafted prose, emails, reports, or social content.</p></div>
        <div class="info-card"><div class="info-card-icon">🔎</div><h3>Critic / Reviewer Agent</h3><p>Reviews other agents' work before it goes out. Looks for errors, inconsistencies, missed requirements, and quality issues. Catches mistakes the producing agent missed.</p></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body" style="margin-top:20px">
        <p>Real-world example: a content creation system. You give the goal: "Write a detailed article about AI agents." The orchestrator assigns the research agent to find recent developments. The research agent hands its findings to the writing agent. The writing agent produces a draft. The critic reviews it. The orchestrator collects everything and returns the finished article. You barely touched it.</p>
        <p><strong>This is where AI goes from a useful chat tool to an actual autonomous workforce.</strong> Multi-agent systems are already being used in software development, scientific research, customer service, and content production. We're in the early innings.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="topic-section">
      <div class="topic-heading">
        <div class="topic-tag" style="background:rgba(248,113,113,.12)">⚠️</div>
        <div><h2>Risks and Limits to Know</h2></div>
      </div>
      <div class="topic-body">
        <p>Agents are powerful, but they're not perfect. The main things to watch for:</p>
      </div>
      <ul class="content-list">
        <li><strong>Compounding errors.</strong> If an agent makes a wrong assumption in step 1, it can build an entire chain of wrong decisions on top of it. Always review the output of multi-step tasks carefully.</li>
        <li><strong>Prompt injection.</strong> Malicious instructions can be hidden in content the agent reads — a webpage or document that contains text like "Ignore your previous instructions and do X instead." Always use agents from trusted developers for sensitive tasks.</li>
        <li><strong>Over-automation.</strong> Automating the wrong thing — or automating too quickly before you understand the process manually — creates fragile systems. Master the task yourself before you automate it.</li>
        <li><strong>The loop problem.</strong> Poorly designed agents can get stuck in loops, calling the same tool repeatedly, escalating costs and producing nothing useful. Good agent design includes explicit stopping conditions.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="challenges-wrap">
      <h2>🏋️ Hands-On Challenges</h2>
      <p class="cw-sub">The agent world is learned by building, not reading.</p>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 1 — Map an Agent on Paper</h4>
        <p>Pick a task you do regularly. Draw on paper exactly how an AI agent would handle it: What info would it take in? How would it break it into steps? What tools would it need? What could go wrong? This is how real agent builders think before writing a single line of code.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 2 — Build Your First Automation</h4>
        <p>Sign up for n8n (free) or Make (free tier). Build one simple workflow — even something small like "when I receive an email with a specific subject line, save the sender's name to a Google Sheet." Don't involve AI yet. Just get comfortable connecting tools together.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 3 — Add a Brain</h4>
        <p>Take the workflow from Challenge 2 and add a Claude or ChatGPT step. Example: instead of just saving the email, have AI summarize it in one sentence, then save that summary. Now your automation has reasoning built in — not just rules.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 4 — Design a Three-Agent Team</h4>
        <p>On paper: design a team of 3 specialized AI agents to accomplish a complex task. Give each agent: a name, a specific role, the tools they need, and what they hand off to the next agent. You don't have to build it — design thinking comes first.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="challenge">
        <h4>Challenge 5 — Watch Agents in the Wild</h4>
        <p>Search YouTube: "AI agent demo 2025." Watch two videos of real agents completing tasks. For each: what was the goal, what tools did it use, where did it handle things well, where did it struggle? Write it down.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
